'''Antoine Sonrel''' (died 1879) was an illustrator, engraver, and photographer in [[Switzerland]] and [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], in the 19th century. He moved from [[Neuchâtel]] to the United States around the late 1840s, and was affiliated with [[Louis Agassiz]] throughout his career.{{refn|group=nb|Sometimes Sonrel's name appears (incorrectly) as "Antoine Sourel",<ref name="Great Industrial Exhibition">{{citation |title=Great Industrial Exhibition |work= Pittsfield Sun |location=Massachusetts |date= April 10, 1851 }}</ref> "August Sonrel,"<ref>{{citation |author=David Starr Jordan |title= Spencer Fullerton Baird and the United States Fish Commission |work= Scientific Monthly |volume= 17 |number= 2 |date=August 1923 }}</ref> "Auguste Sonrel" or "Antoine Sowrel."<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/stream/officialdescrip04goog#page/n762/mode/2up |volume=3 |title=Great Exhibition of the Works of Industry of All Nations, 1851: Official Descriptive and Illustrated Catalogue |location= London |year= 1851 |page=1463 }}</ref>}} As a photographer he created numerous [[carte de visite]] portraits in the 1860s and 1870s; subjects included his friend Agassiz, [[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.]], [[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Jr.]], [[Abbott Lawrence Rotch]], and sculptor [[Anne Whitney]].{{refn|group=nb|Photos by Sonrel reside in the collections of the Massachusetts Historical Society, Smithsonian, Boston Athenaeum, and Harvard University.}}
==Biography==
Around the 1830s in Neuchâtel, Sonrel began creating scientific illustrations for Louis Agassiz. "Draftsmen of superior talent, trained ... to the greatest accuracy — Weber, Dinkel, and Sonrel — were constantly in [Agassiz's] employ at a regular salary. ... At the suggestion of Agassiz an extensive lithographic establishment was created in Neuchatel."<ref>{{citation |author=Guyot |title= Memoir of Louis Agassiz, 1807-1873 |work= Biographical Memoirs |publisher= National Academy of Sciences |orig-year= 1878 |year=1886 }}</ref> Agassiz wrote in 1857: "I esteem myself happy to have been able to secure the continued assistance of my old friend, Mr. A. Sonrel, in drawing the zoological figures of my work. More than twenty years ago, he began to make illustrations for my European works ; and ever since he has been engaged, with short interruptions, in executing drawings for me."<ref>{{cite book |author=Louis Agassiz |title= Contributions to the Natural Nistory of the United States of America |location= Boston |publisher= Little, Brown and Co. |year= 1862 }}</ref>
[[Image:CharlesKDillaway Japanese students bySonrel Smithsonian.jpg|thumb|right|Portrait by Sonrel of C. K. Dillaway with Hanabusa Kotaro, Hiraga Isasaburo, Tsuge Zengo, and Aoki Yoshihira, 19th century (Smithsonian){{refn|group=nb|For more information on Dillaway, see: {{citation |work=WorldCat |url=http://www.worldcat.org/wcidentities/lccn-n99-270165 |title=Dillaway, Charles K. (Charles Knapp) 1804-1889 }}}}]]
[[Image:Dillaway Kotaro Isasaburo Zengo Yoshihira byASonrel MFABoston.jpeg|thumb|right|Portrait by Sonrel of C. K. Dillaway with Hanabusa Kotaro, Hiraga Isasaburo, Tsuge Zengo, and Aoki Yoshihira, 19th century (Museum of Fine Arts, Boston)]]
In the United States, Sonrel lived in Boston on Acorn Street in [[Beacon Hill, Boston|Beacon Hill]] (c. 1850),<ref>{{cite book |title=[[Boston Directory]] |year= 1850 }}</ref> [[Tremont Street]] (c. 1873),<ref name=directory1873>{{cite book |title=[[Boston Directory]] |year= 1873 }}</ref> and in [[Woburn, Massachusetts]] (c. 1852-1874). He kept a studio in Boston at 46 School Street (c. 1860s)<ref>{{cite book |title=Boston Commercial Directory |year=1869 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Illuminated and Illustrated Business Directory of Boston for 1870}}</ref> and Washington Street (c. 1871-1874).<ref name=directory1873 /><ref>{{cite book |title=Boston Almanac |year= 1871 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Woburn Directory |year= 1874 |location=Massachusetts }}</ref> Sonrel exhibited lithographs in the 1851 [[The Great Exhibition|World's Fair]] in London<ref name="Great Industrial Exhibition"/><ref>{{cite book |url=https://www.google.com/books?id=OfMHAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA191 |title=Official Catalogue of the Great Exhibition of the Works of Industry of All Nations |location= London |year= 1851 |page=191 }}</ref> and in the 1853 exhibition of the [[Massachusetts Charitable Mechanic Association]].<ref>{{cite book |title=7th Exhibition of the Massachusetts Charitable Mechanic Association |location= Boston |publisher= Damrell & Moore |year= 1853 }}</ref>
