'''''Cetobacterium somerae''''' is a [[Gram-negative]], [[microaerotolerant]], non-[[spore]]-forming and [[rod-shaped]] bacterium from the genus of ''[[Cetobacterium]]'' which has been isolated from human feces.<ref name=Cetobacterium-somerae/><ref name=UniProt/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Finegold |first1=SM |last2=Vaisanen |first2=ML |last3=Molitoris |first3=DR |last4=Tomzynski |first4=TJ |last5=Song |first5=Y |last6=Liu |first6=C |last7=Collins |first7=MD |last8=Lawson |first8=PA |title=Cetobacterium somerae sp. nov. from human feces and emended description of the genus Cetobacterium |journal=Systematic and Applied Microbiology |date=June 2003 |volume=26 |issue=2 |pages=177–81 |doi=10.1078/072320203322346010 |pmid=12866843}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Details: DSM-23941 |website=www.dsmz.de |url=https://www.dsmz.de/catalogues/details/culture/DSM-23941.html |language=en}}</ref> ''Cetobacterium somerae'' occur in intestinal tracts of [[freshwater fish]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Tsuchiya |first1=C |last2=Sakata |first2=T |last3=Sugita |first3=H |title=Novel ecological niche of Cetobacterium somerae, an anaerobic bacterium in the intestinal tracts of freshwater fish |journal=Letters in Applied Microbiology |date=January 2008 |volume=46 |issue=1 |pages=43–8 |doi=10.1111/j.1472-765X.2007.02258.x |pmid=17944860}}</ref> Cetobacterium somerae produces [[cobalamin]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Merrifield |first1=Daniel L. |last2=Ringo |first2=Einar |title=Aquaculture Nutrition: Gut Health, Probiotics and Prebiotics |date=2014 |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |isbn=9781118897270 |language=en}}</ref>
